article.description:
Steve Francis hit a 3-pointer with one-tenth of a
second left to give the Houston Rockets a 95-92 victory over the Utah Jazz on Sunday.
article.headline: Stockton records 15,000th assist in loss
article.linkText: Rockets' Francis beats clock, Jazz with late 3-pointer
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Steve Francis never had a doubt. Francis hit a 3-pointer with one-tenth of a second left to give the Houston Rockets a 95-92 victory over the Utah Jazz on Sunday. "I actually looked around to see if anybody was open," Francis said. "I knew it was in when it left my hand. I just wanted to be sure there was no time left and I milked it just right." Utah point guard John Stockton had 13 assists to give him exactly 15,000 for his career. Magic Johnson is second on the NBA's all-time list with 10,141. "I appreciate the compliments, but I haven't thought much about it," Stockton said. "We didn't win the game and that's what matters. The record doesn't have anything to do with tonight's game." Cuttino Mobley scored 28 points, including 17 in the second half, and Kenny Thomas had 18 points and nine rebounds as the Rockets ended a two-game losing streak. Francis finished with 16 points. Karl Malone led the Jazz with 21 points. Stockton added 12 points, 10 in the fourth quarter. "It's unfortunate it came when we lost the game, but it doesn't take anything away from his 15,000 assists," Malone said. "It's a tremendous accomplishment for him." The Jazz were upset about a no-call and a technical on Malone late in the game. Kelvin Cato was not called for a foul when he blocked Malone's layup with 1:08 to play. Malone was then assessed a technical for something he said to referee Danny Crawford, and Mobley hit the free throw to tie it at 90 with 34 seconds to play. "Yeah, it was a blocked shot if he blocked my head," Malone said. "(Crawford) said I walked over there and said he was a cheater. I didn't say anything. That's all I want to say about the whole thing. Otherwise, it's going to cost me some money." Predictably, the Rockets saw the play differently. "The ref didn't call a foul so it was no foul," Cato said. "It might have been clean. It felt clean. But most of the time he gets that call." Jazz coach Jerry Sloan only knew Malone felt he was fouled. "I don't have a problem if it's called the same both ways," Sloan said. "We always have something funny with Danny. Something strange always happens with us with him." Stockton hit a layup with five seconds left to tie it at 92. Houston led by as many as nine early in the fourth quarter before Utah rallied late behind Stockton. Terence Morris, starting his 24th game in place of an injured Walt Williams, scored six points as Houston jumped to an 18-8 lead with 4:52 to play in the first. The Rockets led 27-19 after one quarter, with Mobley scoring nine points. Houston scored the first six points of the second quarter to extend its lead to 14 points. But Utah went on an 11-2 run with Donyell Marshall scoring five points to close the gap to 35-30 with 5:31 to play in the half. The Jazz finished the quarter on a 9-0 run, with Marshall scoring seven points to make it 40-39 at the break. Marshall had 12 points in the first half. It was close through most of the third quarter before Mobley's six points sparked a 12-2 run that gave Houston a 65-54 lead with 2:26 left in the period. Despite nine third-quarter points by Malone, Houston still led 67-62 entering the fourth. Mobley had five points in an 8-2 run that pushed the margin back to 77-68 with 9:19 left. But Rusty LaRue scored four points as Utah went on an 11-2 spurt to take an 87-86 lead with 3:01 to play. Eddie Griffin's free throw tied it with 2:27 remaining. "It seems like everything's always against us," Utah's Bryon Russell said. "Cato took off Malone's head. What are we supposed to do?" Game notes
Williams, who missed five weeks with a sprained left ankle before being activated Feb. 25, was out Sunday with the same injury. He re-injured it in Friday's game. Team officials said he is day-to-day. ... Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich passed Billy Cunningham for sole possession of 25th place on the NBA's career wins list with 455. ... Utah is 14-16 on the road, with victories in six of its last eight away from home.
